{
  "lessonAim": "To identify and distinguish between statutory and non-statutory regulations within the electrical industry, ensuring correct classification of key documents like EAWR and BS 7671.",
  "taskMode": "respond",
  "teachCheckCount": 5,
  "teachChecks": [
    {

{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Laws passed by Parliament that are mandatory; failure to follow them is a criminal offense.",
      "anchor": "The Law of the Land.",
      "misconception": "Thinking these are just 'best practice' rather than legal requirements that can lead to prosecution."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Industry standards and guidance that are not law but are used to show you have met legal requirements.",
      "anchor": "The Industry Rulebook.",
      "misconception": "Believing that because they aren't law, they are optional and can be ignored safely."
    },
    {
      "term": "HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The primary UK law governing health and safety in every workplace.",
      "anchor": "The Umbrella Act.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it only applies to the boss; it actually places duties on every employee too."
    },
    {
      "term": "EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory regulations that specifically focus on electrical safety in the workplace.",
      "anchor": "The Electrician's Law.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these legal requirements with the technical rules found in BS 7671."
    },
    {
      "term": "BS 7671",
      "simpleDefinition": "The UK national standard for electrical installations, also known as the Wiring Regulations.",
      "anchor": "The Big Blue Book.",
      "misconception": "Thinking BS 7671 is a statutory law; it is actually a non-statutory standard."
    },
    {
      "term": "On-Site Guide",
      "simpleDefinition": "A non-statutory handbook that simplifies BS 7671 for common, small-scale electrical tasks.",
      "anchor": "The Pocket Guide.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the On-Site Guide covers every complex industrial scenario; it is for basic installations only."
    },
    {
      "term": "Codes of Practice",
      "simpleDefinition": "Non-statutory documents that give practical instructions on how to work safely and meet legal duties.",
      "anchor": "The How-To Guide.",
      "misconception": "Thinking they are just suggestions; they are often used in court to prove what a 'competent person' should have done."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means it's the law.",
    "Non-statutory means it's the standard.",
    "BS 7671 is the industry bible, but it isn't a law.",
    "EAWR is the law you must follow when working with electricity."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "BS 7671 is a statutory regulation.",
    "Non-statutory guidance is optional.",
    "HASAWA only applies to employers.",
    "Statutory and non-statutory mean the same thing."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "The Framework of Electrical Rules",
      "objective": "Explanation A",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the electrical industry, we do not guess how to work safely. We follow a strict framework of rules designed to prevent injury and death. These rules are divided into two main groups: Statutory and Non-statutory.",
        "Statutory means it is a law passed by Parliament. If you break a statutory regulation, you are committing a criminal offense, which can lead to prosecution, heavy fines, or even imprisonment. It is the 'Law of the Land.'",
        "Non-statutory refers to industry standards and guidance. While these are not laws themselves, they are the 'Industry Rulebook' we use to prove we are working to a safe, professional standard. Think of statutory as the 'must-do' legal requirement and non-statutory as the 'how-to' technical guide. Both are essential for a competent electrician to understand and follow."
      ],
      "hint": "Statutory is the law; non-statutory is the professional standard."
    },
    {
      "title": "How Law and Guidance Work Together",
      "objective": "Explanation B",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "A common mistake is thinking that because something is 'non-statutory,' it is optional and can be ignored. In reality, these two types of regulations work together in a legal setting.",
        "If an accident occurs and you end up in court, a judge will first look at the statutory law, such as the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR), to see what your legal duty was. They will then look at the non-statutory guidance, such as BS 7671 (The Wiring Regulations), to see if you followed the industry-standard way of working.",
        "If you ignored the guidance without a valid technical reason, the court will likely decide you failed your legal duty. Therefore, following non-statutory guidance is the primary way an electrician proves they have met their statutory legal obligations. They are not just suggestions; they are the benchmark for safety."
      ],
      "hint": "Following the industry standard (non-statutory) is how you prove you followed the law (statutory)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Statutory Regulations: The Law",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: statutory regulations.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Statutory regulations are mandatory. You have no choice but to follow them. The primary piece of legislation is the Health and Safety at Work Act, often shortened to HASAWA. This is the 'Umbrella Act' that covers every person in every workplace, placing duties on both employers and employees.",
        "Underneath this umbrella, we have more specific laws. The most critical for us is the Electricity at Work Regulations, known as EAWR. This law demands that electrical systems are designed, constructed, and maintained safely to prevent danger. Other statutory examples include PUWER (Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations), which ensures your tools are safe, and the PPE (Personal Protective Equipment at Work) Regulations. Because these are statutory, failing to comply is a criminal act."
      ],
      "hint": "HASAWA and EAWR are examples of statutory laws that must be followed."
    },
    {
      "title": "Non-statutory Regulations: The Standards",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: non-statutory regulations/guidance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory regulations are technical standards. The most famous example is BS 7671, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations or 'The Big Blue Book.' This document is the national standard for electrical installations in the UK. It tells us exactly how to design and install systems to remain safe.",
        "Other non-statutory documents include the On-Site Guide, which is a simplified handbook for common, small-scale tasks, and various Guidance Notes. We also use Codes of Practice and the Unite Union Book. These documents provide the practical, step-by-step instructions on how to be a 'competent person.' While you won't be arrested simply for not owning a copy of BS 7671, failing to follow its technical rules usually means you have failed to meet the legal safety requirements set out in the EAWR."
      ],
      "hint": "BS 7671 and the On-Site Guide are non-statutory industry standards."
    },
    {
      "title": "Identifying Specific Statutory Laws",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: 203.LO1.AC1.1.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To work safely, you must identify which documents are statutory laws. If the title includes 'Act' or 'Regulations' passed by the government, it is statutory. Key examples include HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act) and EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations).",
        "You must also recognize other specific laws: COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health) deals with dangerous chemicals like cleaning fluids or lead. CDM (Construction Design and Management) manages safety and roles on building sites. PUWER (Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations) covers the safety of your drills and testers. Finally, the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations requires employers to carry out risk assessments. If the document is a legal mandate that can lead to a court case, it is categorized as statutory."
      ],
      "hint": "Look for 'Act' or 'Regulations' in the name, such as COSHH, CDM, or EAWR."
    }
  ]
}

